    {
      "id": "GENUS_ARDEA",
      "name": "Ardea",
      "rank": "GENUS",
      "description": "Great herons and egrets — the largest and most familiar members of the family. The grey heron (gråhäger) is one of the most recognisable birds in Sweden: a tall, slate-grey sentinel standing motionless at the water's edge for hours, then striking with lightning speed to impale a fish with its dagger bill. Grey herons nest colonially in tall trees ('heronries') — colonies in Swedish parks and forests can be centuries old and contain hundreds of pairs. The great white egret (ägretthäger) was once so rare in Sweden that a sighting was a national event; following a dramatic European range expansion it now breeds in southern Swedish marshes and is increasingly common as a winter visitor in Stockholm.",
      "lineage": "Grey Herons & Egrets",
      "children": [
        {
          "id": "ARDEA_CINEREA",
          "name": "Ardea cinerea",
          "rank": "SPECIES",
          "commonName": "Grey heron",
          "lineage": "Grey Herons & Egrets",
          "continents": [
            "Europe",
            "Asia",
            "Africa"
          ],
          "subspeciesCount": 4,
          "description": "The grey heron is a long-legged wading bird of the heron family, Ardeidae, native throughout temperate Europe and Asia, and also parts of Africa. It is resident in much of its range, but some populations from the more northern parts migrate southwards in autumn. A bird of wetland areas, it can be seen around lakes, rivers, ponds, marshes and on the sea coast.",
