      "description": "Bitterns — cryptically camouflaged, reedbed-dwelling herons with one of the most extraordinary vocalisations in the animal kingdom. The great bittern's 'boom' — a deep, resonant foghorn-like sound carrying up to 5 km — is produced by inflating specialised air sacs in the oesophagus and is most often heard at dawn and dusk in early spring. Bitterns are masters of camouflage: their brown, streaked plumage matches reedbeds perfectly, and when alarmed they stretch upward with bill pointing skyward, swaying gently to mimic reeds in the wind. The Swedish rördrom is a thinly distributed and declining breeding bird, requiring extensive reedlands that are being lost to drainage and water level management.",
